{{Infobox book | name = Concepts of Modern Mathematics | title_orig = | translator = | image = Concepts of Modern Mathematics.jpg | caption = Softcover edition | author = [[Ian Stewart (mathematician)|Ian Stewart]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | series = | subject = Mathematics | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = Dover publication | pub_date = 1975 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print | pages = 352 pages | isbn = 0-14-021849-1 | dewey = 510 | congress = QA93 .S73 | oclc = 2020912 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Concepts of Modern Mathematics''''' is a 1975 book by mathematician and science popularizer [[Ian Stewart (mathematician)|Ian Stewart]] about recent developments in [[mathematics]].<ref name="heuer">Review of the 1995 Dover reprint of the 1981 edition, by G. A. Heuer (1996), {{mr|1319145}}.</ref>
==Overview== The book arose out of an extramural class that Ian Stewart taught at the [[University of Warwick]] about "Modern mathematics".<ref name="heuer"/> In the 1995 [[Dover Publications|Dover]] edition Stewart wrote that the aim of the class was:
:''to explain why the underlying abstract point of view had gained currency among research mathematicians, and to examine how it opened up entirely new realms of mathematical thought''.
The book is aimed at non-mathematicians. However, there are frequent equations and diagrams and the level of presentation is more technical than some of Stewart's other popular books such as ''[[Flatterland]]''. Topics covered include [[analytic geometry]], [[set theory]], [[abstract algebra]], [[group theory]], [[topology]], and [[probability]].
