In mathematics, '''Mumford's compactness theorem''' states that the space of [[compact space|compact]] [[Riemann surface]]s of fixed [[genus (mathematics)|genus]] ''g''&nbsp;>&nbsp;1 with no [[closed geodesic]]s of length less than some fixed ''&epsilon;''&nbsp;>&nbsp;0 in the [[Poincaré metric]] is compact. It was proved by {{harvs|txt|first=David|last=Mumford|authorlink=David Mumford|year=1971}} as a consequence of a theorem about the compactness of sets of discrete subgroups of [[semisimple Lie group]]s generalizing [[Mahler's compactness theorem]].
